&gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt; This ability to evolve the application flow of web apps is due almost
&gt; &gt; entirely to the sophistication of the human brain. Machine agents do
&gt; &gt; not behave this way. If you have evidence showing they can, please
&gt; &gt; share it.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; The thing is however, that REST enables communication to *happen* even if
&gt; the intended application fails to run into a success state in the end. REST
&gt; clients (i.e. HTTP clients) will be able to handle all possible kinds of
&gt; error states (by virtue of implementing HTTP completely) and we will
&gt; generally be able to proceed(!) from failure states at a much more
&gt; sophisticated level than with a broken RPC application. The latter just
&gt; dies with some convoluted exception in some log in some obscure location.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; For me, leveraging the power of HTTP as-is is at the heart of applying
&gt; REST successfully - we need not seek for building AI into clients - that&#39;s
&gt; an illusion anyhow.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;

Ok, this is all fine - I&#39;m not sure that anyone was suggesting this is not
the case. We got to this point because we were discussing whether or not a
server should &#39;know&#39; about the part of an application it is responsible for
dealing with. I&#39;m still not convinced that a server can &#39;know nothing&#39;
about a given resource&#39;s role but, at the same time, be able to process
requests to it in a specific way.

To be honest, this conversation isn&#39;t really going anywhere and hasn&#39;t been
for some time. I still feel there are unanswered questions from much
further back in the thread that are worth exploring, maybe we should head
back to them or just drop this entirely?

Cheers,
Mike

